    "key": "YARN-2487",
    "fields": {
      "summary": "Need to support timeout of AM When no containers are assigned to it for a defined period",
      "issuetype": {
        "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/issuetype/4",
        "id": "4",
        "description": "An improvement or enhancement to an existing feature or task.",
        "iconUrl": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/viewavatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=21140&avatarType=issuetype",
        "name": "Improvement",
        "subtask": false,
        "avatarId": 21140
      },
      "components": [
        {
          "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/component/12319322",
          "id": "12319322",
          "name": "resourcemanager"
        }
      ],
      "subtasks": [],
      "created": "2014-09-02T02:39:16.786+0000",
      "description": " There are some scenarios where AM will not get containers and indefinitely waiting. We faced one such sceanrio which makes the applications to get hung : \nConsider a cluster setup which has 2 NMS of each 8GB resource,\nAnd 2 applications(MR2) are launched in the default queue where in each AM is taking 2 GB each.\nEach AM is placed in each of the NM. Now each AM is requesting for container of 7Gb  mem resource .\nAs in each NM only 6GB resource is available both the applications are hung forever.\n\nTo avoid such scenarios i would like to propose \ngeneric timeout feature for all AM's in yarn, such that if no containers are assigned for an application for a defined period than yarn can timeout the application attempt.\nDefault can be set to 0 where in RM will not timeout the app attempt and user can set his own timeout when he submits the application",
      "priority": {
        "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/priority/3",
        "iconUrl": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/priorities/major.svg",
        "name": "Major",
        "id": "3"
      },
